{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626276"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:35:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:35:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17066"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17066"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.06,0.06,0.61,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69097"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9756"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17066"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54554"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3652"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5281"},{"type":"tags","id":"11187"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22934"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23149"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69097"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman is diagnosed with Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV). Her doctor discusses starting combination antiretroviral therapy that includes a protease inhibitor. They explain that different antiretroviral medications can target different stages of the HIV life cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of HIV protease inhibitors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevents viral RNA transcription","Inhibits viral DNA integration","Blocks viral entry into host cells","Prevents cleavage of viral polyproteins","Inhibits viral reverse transcriptase"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHIV protease inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing cleavage of viral polyproteins\u003C/strong\u003E into functional components. This prevents the formation of mature, infectious viral particles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking viral entry into host cells\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of entry inhibitors like enfuvirtide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting viral reverse transcriptase\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of nucleoside and non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting viral DNA integration\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of integrase inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreventing viral RNA transcription\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism targeted by current antiretroviral drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of protease inhibitors include darunavir, atazanavir, and lopinavir. They are characterized by the suffix \u0027-navir\u0027 and are used as part of combination antiretroviral therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["HIV protease inhibitors work by blocking viral protease enzymes that cleave viral polyproteins into functional proteins needed for viral maturation.","Without functional protease enzymes, HIV cannot produce mature, infectious viral particles.","Protease inhibitors are characterized by their \u0027-navir\u0027 suffix and are used as part of combination antiretroviral therapy."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54554"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17066"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54554"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T09:17:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T22:26:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9756"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69097"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science